The Republican Strategy of Resistance to the Re-Election of Obama
The Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat electoral falsifications.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, claiming that cases of election falsification in the United States are rarer than cases of lightning death.
In addition, Republican lawyers counted only 300 cases of electoral falsifications in the United States over a decade.
One thing can be said with confidence: these new trends will have a negative impact on the turnout of voters.
In this sense, such actions partly discredit the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for organising federal elections in the United States.
That is why most state governments have passed laws since 2009 that complicate the process of registration or voting.
This phenomenon gained new momentum after the November 2010 elections, which brought Republicans 675 new seats in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were passed in a single year in 2011, restricting the right to vote in 41 states.
The new election laws require the voter to present a photo ID and proof of the existence of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws shorten the period of early voting, abolish the right to register a voter on the day of expression of will, and deprive citizens of the right to vote who have a criminal record.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana became the first state to introduce such a requirement.
In 2008, the U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of Indiana’s law.
The Republican authorities hurried to spread this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have initiated bills requiring voters to present photo IDs in 34 states.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have such a universal identity card as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, that is, 21 million people who have reached the required voting age, do not have an identity card with a photo issued by their state government body.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a document.
At the same time, the cost of obtaining the required identity card often exceeds one hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65, and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required photo ID.
But that's not all.
Students - voters who are believed to vote for Democratic candidates - are not allowed in several states to use a photo ID issued by their educational institution.
But these same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, who vote mainly for Republicans, to use for voting the certificates issued by these clubs.
Until 2004, no state required proof of U.S. citizenship for voting.
This requirement was first introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than 10 states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are obviously aimed at limiting the voting of Latin American people.
It is estimated that two-thirds of Latin American voters vote in favor of the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers initiated laws in 2011 that abolished the registration of voters on the day of the vote in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals or groups to provide assistance to those wishing to register.
This restriction did not pass without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 elections, the voter registration campaign helped to add about 10 million citizens to the lists.
At the same time, the measures taken since 2009 have led to a 17 per cent drop in the level of registration of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have passed laws in five other states aimed at shortening the period of early voting.
Thus, during the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of voters who voted early were African-Americans, although the latter accounted for only 13% of the state’s total electorate.
The same thing happened with the Latin American natives.
Representing only 11% of the electorate, they made up 24% of the citizens who voted early.
In contrast to whites, who made up 76% of the electorate, only 46% of those who voted prematurely.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters are actively opposed to the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
Several bills were vetoed by Democratic governors.
The most ambiguous laws were suspended with the intervention of the Attorney General of the United States.
This has helped to partially limit the negative consequences.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed laws requiring photo IDs to be presented.
However, the new rules that came into force would certainly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote in the 2012 elections.
Critics of the Democrats condemn the bias of the laws that have been passed, seeing them as a clear focus on influencing the results of the 2012 elections in key states.
The Brennan Center’s 2011 report shows that states that pass these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes required in the college of electors to win the presidential election.
It is too early to assert with confidence that these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
Only one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the turnout of voters.
In this sense, such actions partly discredit the system of American democracy.
Screening for prostate cancer: to pass the test or not?
