Higgs boson in detail
Last summer, the news that scientists may have been able to detect the Higgs boson caused real excitement — and not without reason.
It is believed that this boson explains the mass of all the particles in the universe, neither much nor little.
Moreover, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted within the framework of the Standard Model - our best, or at least the "least imperfect" description of nature and the behavior of matter - but which has not previously been detected by experimental means.
But physicists are not yet sure that this is the Higgs boson.
We know, without a shadow of a doubt, that we are dealing with a really new particle and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, the new data presented this week at a major physical convention in Kyoto seems to confirm this, although some data is not yet enough for complete certainty.
Let's imagine that we are talking about the Higgs boson, because the chances of making a mistake seem minimal, and let's see what that means.
There is, in this world, one law absolutely inevitable, which states that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to circumvent this rule, do not even try too hard, otherwise you will hurt yourself.
But although the physics of elementary particles is a rather strange world, it turns out that there is also one law of a similar nature: the Pauli exclusion principle, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantum state" in the same characteristics, is the "state behind".
Based on this, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find well-ordered citizens, called farms, who wisely obey Pauli’s principle.
In another there are bosons, a hideous gang of anarchists, who have no respect for anything - at least for this principle, which means that they can quietly find themselves in the same place at the same time.
As reported by the site (by the way, quite unusual) Particle Adventure Laboratory Berkeley, these bosons are divided, in turn, into two groups: mesons, which we will not talk about here, and "particles of force", through which the main forces of nature are distributed and to which in some way the bosons are removed.
These same bosons, it should be emphasized, are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it’s because of one incredibly banal boson: a photon, or “particle of light,” which is a “curator” of electromagnetic force.
In fact, when one particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "breaks" the electromagnetic field at that particular location, about like a stone thrown into a pond.
From this "disruption" an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore one of the bosons of "force carriers".
A more stable field.
The same is true of the Higgs boson, with the only difference that in order for this boson to appear, another field, the Higgs field, must be "broken."
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; in order to excite it, it is necessary to achieve very and very high energies, as if it were a frozen pond, the surface of which could only be shaken by a very large stone.
That's why we need a huge particle accelerator like the one that operates in CERN - the Large Hadron Collider, which is a ring with a diameter of 27 km! - to achieve such huge energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is also useful for explaining the relationship between the Higgs boson and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, interact, while others do not: a sheet of paper, for example, will never hold itself in the refrigerator.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact have mass, while others (like photons, by the way) do not.
So, what “can bring” all this research, asks Mrs. Plamondon?
In science, they are used to verify the correctness of the Standard Model (SM), and this also allows physicists to find a discrepancy between the results of observations and the predictions of SM.
In addition, some of them passionately long for such a discrepancy to be discovered, because the slightest inconsistency can open the door to "new physics" and shut some of the Model's holes.
The latter, it must be said, still has significant drawbacks, offering no explanation for gravity (oh!) or for the dark matter that forms about 80% of the universe (oh-oh!).
But so far, no such discrepancies have been found in CERN.
Consequences
The benefit of these studies for the daily life of the average person is harder to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that it is not.
In the early 1960s, the pioneers of laser research in Bell’s labs could not even guess what a revolution their work would cause.
They predicted their applications in science, but nothing more.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at the Bella Laboratories, where a laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (previous ones were pulsed) in 1962, said that the laser was originally considered more like a "laboratory gag".
Suppose...
In addition, the application can be found for the tools accompanying the study.
For example, the same William Boyle during his optical studies in 1969 developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, although not at all its original purpose, now serves as the “eye” for all the digital cameras in the world and earned the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
This, of course, does not mean that the work of the Large Hadron Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it only shows, in fact, that everything can be.
