53% of patients admitted to the Victor-Gadboa shelter come from home, and 47% from the hospital.
The problem of access to palliative care
It is estimated that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, to care that is provided to alleviate the suffering of patients entering the final stage of their lives, whether at home, in the hospital or in the shelter.
And some institutions, such as the Victor-Gadbua shelter and the Greater Montreal Palliative Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in caring for cancer patients.
It is this huge gap in Quebec’s health care system that makes many palliative care practitioners fear the adoption of a law that legalizes euthanasia and assists suicide.
Starting in October, a manifesto signed by palliative care lights, Dr. Balfour Mountain and Dr. Bernard Lapuant, circulating and testifying to their disagreement with such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christian Martel, Quebec’s healthcare system is not efficient enough to provide the right to high-quality palliative care before the transition to euthanasia is allowed.
“Recently,” she says, “I saw a patient who spent 14 days in the ambulance, in terrible pain, and no one took the necessary measures to relieve them.
I'm afraid that patients want to die just because they don't get adequate care.
At the same time, many oncologists try to save patients until the last day, despite pessimistic forecasts.
Hopes for Ellen Richard’s survival were already minimal when she stopped debilitating chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she replied that she regretted that I was stopping the fight.
She told me that my days were numbered.
There is no almighty care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask for death thank the medical staff for not fulfilling their request, after the palliative care team relieves their pain.
However, it should be noted that palliative care is not absolutely omnipotent in the fight against pain.
According to Elsie Monroe, director of palliative care at the Greater Montreal Palliative Care Society, patients are not susceptible to anesthesia in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, in which the patient sleeps until he dies, either occasionally or permanently.
We can no longer pretend that we do not know about these sufferings.
Increasingly, patients who are unable to relieve pain will be able to access palliative sedation.
Patients suffering from pain always say the same phrase: "I want to die."
But it doesn’t necessarily mean “I want to be euthanized,” it means “I want to feel better.”
