About 200,000 operations have already been recorded from 15,000 computers on the network.
Several thousand sites accept bitcoins for donations or as a means of payment.
The bitcoin exchange rate, peaking at $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later before returning to about $10 today (the rates are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing special compared to the world exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) took an interest in the system in its report on virtual currency published in October.
He describes bitcoin as “the most successful virtual currency,” “competitive with the dollar or the euro,” and “similar to conventional currencies.”
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies, such as “credits” used to promote the video game, which are earned during the game or which can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But exchange operations are always controlled and processed by some central authority.
In Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are simultaneously bookkeepers, auditors, currency issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually happens between two e-mail addresses, just like an e-mail.
Only for each new payment can the user choose a different address, thus ensuring anonymity.
The set of information relating to this transaction is signed electronically, using a double-key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is possible to verify that the bitcoins used in the transaction actually exist in a public ledger sent across the network.
The key step is to register a new transaction in this book.
It goes through the solution of a mathematical problem sent to computers, which, like a temporary central bank, is given the privilege of adding this new line.
This is the hashing phase of a file, that is, converting a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers "take" a new transaction and add a number to it before "hashing" everyone together.
The goal is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes easily check that it is correct.
The transaction thus turns out to be inextricably linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
If, for the purpose of deception, the user would very quickly (in less than ten minutes) want to pay twice with the same money, only one of these two transactions would be confirmed by the network - and the other would remain unconfirmed, as they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solves the problem receives 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, the reward is regularly split in half, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to one hundred million, which leaves another reserve.
The complexity of the task also increases with increasing computing power.
The life of the network has already experienced ups and downs.
Sites providing Bitcoin services were attacked, and bitcoins were stolen from reserves.
“The defect used does not affect the protocol itself,” assures Pierre Nouaze, who recently launched Paymium, a company that makes payments with real money using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reported on the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this drawback.
Major players, such as Wikipedia, refuse to accept donations of this kind.
Others, such as the WordPress blog platform, allow them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the ledger and found that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
"Gigant Sales" was announced in November.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” rejoices Ion Holmquist, who works at Coinabul, which deals with the conversion of bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Nouaz, another author of the manual on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as an operating network.
Its system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (in real money) or contactless payment through a mobile phone, but it uses Bitcoin to verify transactions, which thus comes out cheaper.
The owner has better control over their personal data and can thus be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for entrepreneurs who do not need to install new devices or software.
All you need to do is provide an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by the phone, Pierre Nouaze clarifies, assuring that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general tendency to revise hierarchical systems in favor of more horizontal ones.
“It will take some time before Bitcoin is established, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
The ECB, in its report, proposes, by the way, to revise the various risks that are considered high today, in case of success of this system.
