Difficult Births of the Constitution of Egypt
This is a risky new move by President Mohamed Morsi.
While Egypt is divided more than ever on the issue of a constitutional declaration that temporarily gives it extraordinary powers, it has decided to play the va-bank.
Surprisingly, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on the final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state gave the Assembly two additional months to complete the work.
For almost two years, Egypt has been relying on a preliminary text that has been amended several times, weakening institutional stability and leading to legal contradictions.
This new initiative has only increased the division of the country.
According to his opponents, the President persists in his "autocratic delusion", continuing to "violate this word" and "violate the right".
In the camp, his followers believe that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis by accelerating the transition process.
The referendum must be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time, which forces the Brothers to abandon the intention to explain to the Egyptians the text, article by article.
For the president, it is also a way to restore social and democratic legitimacy, while discontent rages across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote positively, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Moreover, the call for an accelerated vote is like an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: “Either you vote for my text, or I leave myself extraordinary powers” which are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
In this strange atmosphere, 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, mostly Islamists, voted yesterday for the text.
Most liberals have not responded to the challenge.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they knocked on the door, feeling unable to express their opinion.
Representatives of human rights defenders, religious minorities or civil society did the same.
In order to reach the necessary quorum, 11 people, spare participants, were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that in most cases the articles were voted unanimously.
The commentators, by the way, were amused by the fact that one of the few disagreements of the day arose around . . . time for prayer, as some members of the committee felt that the hours of the Constituent Assembly were set incorrectly.
The text, which was still voted on yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
The object of general attention, article 2 ultimately remained the same article in the 1971 Constitution, which states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for which the introduction of Islamic law is one of the main requirements, hoped to replace "principles" with "rules", which would make it possible to apply them more strictly.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is a testament to their goodwill and respect for other participants in Egyptian society.
"Lycemery," answer the liberals, who see it only as a pira.
Because, in their opinion, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
They point in particular to article 220, which gives Al-Azhar a consultative role, in particular with regard to the verification of compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pomier, this is alarming, because “people called to make decisions are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.”
We can see the rise of theocracy.”
Many liberals, moreover, are excited by the fact that the next rector of this university seems to be far less moderate than the current one.
“There is no specific religious intervention at the moment.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of civil law.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulems, but people with a university education, some were trained in the French system," reassured Alexis Bloe, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he admits that "around article 220 there may be ambiguity, since the terms used in it are borrowed from religious lexicon.
This applies in particular to the "fikh" [Islamic jurisprudence, see ed.].
And in the future, there may be a question of how competent civil judges are to make decisions about it.”
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is subject to criticism because it gives broad powers to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim brothers claim that they have been significantly reduced compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another controversial point: the powers of the army.
According to the wishes of the military, the consideration of the defense budget will take place not in Parliament, but in the National Defense Council.
Nor will the trial of civilians in military courts be prohibited, despite the requests of human rights associations.
The latter also expressed concern about the text, which they considered to be detrimental to freedom.
The responsibility for blasphemy remains, and insults are now prohibited, which can have serious consequences for freedom of speech, and especially for freedom of the press.
In addition, none of the articles talk about the protection of women anymore, emphasizes Heba Moraef, from Human Rights Watch.
The only positive point, she said, was the prohibition of torture in article 36.
A word that did not appear in the previous Constitution.
