Poland and space.
Last week, at the meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of the ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and in subsequent years took an active part in a number of ESA projects.
But Poland’s journey to space began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in space flights, but this was not always met with understanding.
I will recall, for example, the lecture by A. Sternfeld, who presented ideas from his groundbreaking work "Introduction to Cosmonautics" at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933.
The ideas of the young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, after several years Sternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltry and André Louis Hirsch Prize for "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomsky (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great propagandist of astronomy and space science.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and has written a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a world-renowned propagandist of space science, and his contribution was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the back of the Moon was named in his honor.
Already in 1925 in Poland was built a railway dredge, equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remained unknown, as well as the details of the project.
It is not even clear whether a rocket should have been used to accelerate or brake the truck.
Information about this dress is known only from the press of that era.
Since 1933, the Polish artillery began to think about missile arrows.
The study was carried out by the Armament Technology Section in cooperation with professors Mechislav Wolfka and Gustav Mokzicki.
From the materials preserved, it can be seen that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of the German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the idea of a photoelectric missile-fighter, which was proposed by the engineer Rogozinsky, appeared in the specialized press, and the following year came the work "Air missile-torpedo and aviation missile-bomb" by the author Lelya-Kjivoblotsky.
Both projects were designed for military use of rocket engines.
Prior to the war, the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all the projects of military use of missile technology, which coordinated all the work.
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity, the work was completed due to the outbreak of war.
The next scientific work, devoted to space science, appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, the society is mentioned in the November issue of the journal "Problems", which publishes four voluminous articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich proposed to organize a society that will engage in space science.
At the time, artificial satellite projects were already gaining momentum, and it was clear that space exploration was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (POA) has tried to join the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951), and already in the fall POA became its actual member.
The following year, the first chairman of the International Astronautical Federation, Kazimierz Zarankevich (1902-1959), became vice-chairman of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the POA has made a significant contribution to the development of the very successful meteorological missile RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The missile, capable of covering a distance of 1800 m, was about 80 cm in length and weighed less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, a two-stage RM-2 missile was tested in the Bled desert.
This missile was about 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the missile was already able to carry out real scientific work - the RM-34 missile could overcome 14.5 km, and its task was to observe the high-altitude wind.
In 1962, however, further development was halted.
The successor of the first RM-type missiles was the Meteor-1 missile, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm, and the initial weight - 32.5 kg.
Three types (designated as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed in the size of the camera for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space of 0.4 l, Meteor-1B - 0.34 l, and Meteor-1S - 0.62 l.
The maximum flight range for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with a launch weight of 380 kg was able to bring a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
The Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 versions were then built.
It is also worth mentioning the accession of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee on Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
In addition, as part of the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslav Germashevsky became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
