"Operation Argo: When There's Nothing Worse, Call Hollywood"
In November 1979, a mob of Islamist student demonstrators seized the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the overthrown Shah of Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who fled after the revolution in the United States, who had been the patron of his regime for decades.
For the U.S. administration, a positive outcome was not expected - it could not afford to throw the chess overboard, because it could fundamentally undermine the confidence of allies in other countries.
However, to achieve the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, she was not able.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later reinforced by a failed attempt to free the hostages by force.
The detained diplomats were finally released 444 days later, after negotiations mediated by the Algerian government.
Their fate caused a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments at home.
The defeat in Iran greatly contributed to the defeat of Jimmy Carter in the 1980 presidential election, which ended with the election of Ronald Reagan.
The film, directed by actor Ben Affleck, “Operation Argo” describes one of the episodes of the story that brought America small victories.
Shortly before the occupation of the embassy, six workers managed to escape.
After difficult tours, they ended their journey at the residence of the Canadian Embassy.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to take them out of Iran, aided by an extravagant cover legend that they went on Canadian passports as members of a film crew searching the country for a place to shoot a science fiction epic.
Combination of genres
The plan, invented by evacuation expert Tony Mendes, required Hollywood’s cooperation.
In order for the legend to be credible, specialized magazines wrote about the project of the film, arranged press conferences, a fictional production company had a real office.
The details of the operation have long been kept secret, a film based on the memoirs of Tony Mendes.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several genres.
On the one hand, the real political thriller, the so-called "movie-movie", the story of a successful venture, an affair - an example can be a number of films about friends of Owen.
The film is constantly changing moods - on the one hand, documented scenes from Tehran (the titles show iconic historical photographs of events and how the same situations were demonstrated in the film - there are no big differences in this).
On the other hand, light Hollywood passages intersect with irony and moderate exaggeration.
And then the scenes from the headquarters of the CIA and other institutions - the men in suits discuss the situation at the negotiating tables, on the stairs of the institutions, on the phone ...
Ben Affleck was able to re-start his career.
From a mocking actor became a respected director, and his play ceased to be the object of ridicule.
"Operation Argo" is his third feature film, after the dark detective "Goodbye, Baby, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "City" (2010).
At the same time, this is the first film by Affleck that is not made in the director’s hometown of Boston.
The feeling of the atmosphere of the place refers to the qualities that exalted the director’s earlier films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck shows it in Argo, where Teheran is playing Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place on the streets, in the reconstruction of real events - the introductory scenes of the fall of the embassy impress with their clarity, which also conveys the emotions of confusion and unpredictability that arise when the story suddenly changes somewhere.
A similar effect is achieved by Affleck and his colleagues in the fictional scenes (fake headquarters in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many processes in too many places.
The director had to deal with the fact that the narrative does not involve many exciting scenes of cinematic significance.
He works quite successfully with this little, sometimes something thinks - there it all comes out not so elegant (the scene in which a phone call in America prevents the imminent crisis at the airport of Tehran, and the chase on the runway look pretty naughty).
The disadvantage of Argo is the dispersion associated with the need to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman in the role of Hollywood colleagues are indeed very charming, but their characters would deserve more space, and they are far from the only ones in the film.
Affleck’s film lacks a bit of drama, it’s a film that can be watched with moderate interest, appreciating the production and retro style recreating the thrillers of the seventies.
But it's hard to capture.
However, this is enough to remind us of one, still in the known sense of living history, as well as to testify to the exaggeration of the notions of omnipotent and omniscient special services.
