The EU’s controversial provisions include, for example, the mandatory addition of biocomponents to fuel, which as a result harms nature, as well as a ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers only because they contain a relatively small number of hazardous substances, or a directive on the size of a cell for chickens.
Critics also criticized the factual ban on the use of the term "butterfly oil" or the withdrawal from the sale of classic bulbs.
Quality bananas should be 14 centimeters long.
The pan-European apparatus often makes decisions under the pressure of a trade or industrial lobby, whose positions in Brussels are usually defended by a state or group of states (thus the Czech Republic now even under the threat of a veto defends the claims of its banks).
The interests of the lobby are as follows: for example, the highest quality bananas in the European Union had to reach a length of 14 cm and did not dare to show an "anomalous curvature".
At the same time, the Commission justified itself by harmonizing only the existing divergent national rules that made trade difficult.
The EU, despite the resistance of some states, has still softened standards on fruits and vegetables, citing that existing directives will lead to the waste of products.
Last year’s EU regulation that balloons sold must be provided with a warning that children under the age of eight cannot inflate them without adult supervision could also be a candidate for the prize in the poll.
The EU has turned to American studies, according to which balloons while playing are a potential cause of death of children through choking.
