The architects of MVRDV prove that real adventures are not only in the imagination - on the example of Speikeniss and his recently built Book Mountain - 2 photos
“I think this building is fun, it looks futuristic, finally we can see something interesting again,” says Lizette Verhaig, passing by the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT specialist at a large company located nearby, says: "No, this building is really beautiful."
But I ask myself, why do we have another library today?
Everyone has the Internet, iPad, and e-books.
No one wants to go to these old-fashioned libraries, right?
Spaekenisse, an unremarkable dormitory town near Rotterdam, holds an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
To combat this annoying circumstance a few years ago, it was decided to contribute to general education and to build seven imaginary bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes, in the form of painted miniatures of reinforced concrete.
The success of this educational initiative was modest.
And then the fathers of the city realized that they had the only way to overcome the statistics: to build a library here!
Winnie Maas of the Rotterdam-based architectural firm MVRDV, a master of bold column diagrams and author of witty, sometimes even cynical constructions, addressed the challenge with his usual indiscretion and appeared at a competitive audition in 2003 with five books under his mouse and ear.
And while the jury members scrutinized and shrugged their shoulders, the daring Maas put together a pyramid from his original gift in size and concluded the speech in defense of his project with the following words: "Dear citizens!"
Here it is, my proposal: "Book Mountain" in Speikeniss, the so-called Buckenberg!
Nine years later, this mountain, worth 30 million euros, grew.
It is part of the revitalization project, which also includes an underground garage, a supermarket, a post office and several adjacent residential houses and townhouses for a total of 50 apartments.
In early November, the Book Mountain was awarded the second prize of the "Best Library of the Netherlands 2012" competition.
The project also participates in the 2012 Dutch National Competition for Wooden Structures.
Thus, the faceless suburb, which before could offer nothing but a postmodern pedestrian zone and a surprisingly ugly town hall, whose white facades suggest a dairy factory, became richer in one modern work of architecture.
But the most important thing is that in Spaykenis, the first public building of cultural purpose appeared in the history of this city.
The Long Road to the Book
First impression: the book Eldorado under the cap for cheese.
There is only one lift in the center of the mountain range, because true fans of architecture and reading will prefer to explore this area on foot.
The glazed room on all sides is bright and easily visible, the floors of the burnt brick and the elegant street lights unmistakably create the feeling of a public city square.
The urban environment is perfectly recreated.
The gaze involuntarily looks for benches, dogs and football-playing boys and girls.
And everywhere - books, books, books.
"Usually book shelves stand along the facades, and in the middle there is a large dark hall, usually uncomfortable and faceless," says Vinny Maas.
We put the classic configuration of the space from head to toe and pulled the reading area from the inside out.
The inner space of the mountain of books has been skillfully used: in the center there are offices, an Internet library, a chess club, an environmental center and technical premises.
Particularly pleased are the black book shelves, which serve as decoration of the walls, parapets, staircase railings.
Their appearance, texture and smell are unusual.
Even skilled architects and construction engineers get lost in guessing what kind of unknown material it is.
“We sought to work with secondary materials,” explains Jop Trauborst, project manager representing the Speikenisse community, in line with the standard’s requirements.
And once at a farm in Friesland we found a suitable by-product of agriculture.
For many years in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands, an artificial fibrous material of millimetre thickness has been used as a lining for the roots.
It is cheap and saves time.
Thin textiles serve for one or two seasons, after which it can be discarded.
For the library, this canvas - for the first time in such volumes - was pressed into a panel four centimeters thick.
Under the action of heat and pressure, the so-called landbauplasty (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, durable material, smelling a little like a new car and a little like sneakers.
There are 105 steps to the top.
Those who overcome the almost 500-metre-long path will be rewarded in the literary café not only with fantastic views of the city, but also with Dutch croquets and wooden ficuses in pots.
They care about the atmosphere, and first of all about the correct humidity of the air on the literary mountain.
The cost of a new soul
“It’s hard to believe, but this building, despite its many glass surfaces, is a model project in terms of ecology,” says Trouborst.
For its heating and cooling, the heat of the earth is used.
Although the Book Mountain stands under a glass hood, even on clear days the sun only gets inside for a short time.
Wide glued-wood farms located perpendicular to the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade give shade and absorb most of the sun’s rays.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
The rest of the protection is provided by fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, a skeptic from the field of IT mentioned above, has already visited the new library.
Lizette Verheugen was also already here.
Cynthia Bogard, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, called Buckenberg “the soul of Speikeniss, who had long been lacking.”
The reason: a few weeks before the opening, each resident was invited to donate one book from their own collection.
These books were supposed to occupy empty shelves in a library not yet fully staffed - at that time there were 70,000 books in it.
The idea worked.
Shelves are forced up.
“There’s nothing worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Winnie Maas.
“I think thanks to our invitation, every resident is now somehow connected to this new home.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it is only for decoration.
Thus, MVRDV managed to solve the royal task, which in professional jargon is called identity creation.
Spaykenisse wrote his literary history.
And let them be very young and uneducated.
This is just the starting point for identity building.
“The Germans must play a more important role.”
Germany abstained in the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
According to Stephen Sabo, an expert on U.S.-Europe relations, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic track.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first made it clear that it would vote against the Palestinians’ application for observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained in the vote.
- Why?
Stephen Sabo: Germany does not support Israeli actions in Gaza.
Germany needs to be cautious about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don’t think she supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence – without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained in a vote to impose a no-fly zone.
In the end, NATO made this proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, namely, it is moving from the policy, which, so to speak, was governed by the United States, to the German foreign policy itself.
In addition, the situation is complicated by the fact that Europeans do not have a common policy.
Thus, the Germans again find themselves between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that for the time being they are only looking at their role, but they are on the way to a “more normal” foreign policy.
The kind of foreign policy that France or Britain pursues.
What exactly does “normal” foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
This is a willingness to take a position in their national interests that is independent of the position of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, that is, on exports and ties with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany’s economic interests differ greatly from those of other major states, and therefore Germany must defend its interests.
Have these economic interests affected the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf states.
It therefore needs to be careful not to offend the public and the elite in the Arab countries.
In any case, it plays a role.
But I wouldn’t attach too much importance to it, it’s not a completely one-sided relationship.
But in any case, it plays an important role in the calculations of the Germans.
Has Germany harmed its relations with the United States by abstaining from important decisions such as the vote on Palestine?
I am sure that in Europe and even in the United States the understanding of the German position prevails.
So I don’t think it was as dramatic a headline as the Libyan issue.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect in this way.
After all, this signals that she should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that her interests should be taken into account.
There are different opinions in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the contrary, has clearly expressed its veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the United States and many European countries?
Because of U.S. domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama administration has a deep understanding of the European position.
But due to the local political situation, the government cannot openly take such a position.
I believe that significant differences of opinion are not as significant as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about Netanyahu’s policies.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the US on the one hand and the position of the most important partner in the EU on the other?
I think that’s what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would have been a little easier for the Germans if there had been a unified, uncontradictory European policy, but that is not the case now.
Therefore, they cannot take a broader approach and are forced to act instead, relying only on their own vision of the situation.
That’s how they deal with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will take a leading role in developing a common European position.
It is clear that this is not easy for Germany, at least because of its ties with Israel.
This topic has always been tricky.
But I think it is clear to the Germans that they should play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, won’t it really take on the lead role?
Or is the leading role still difficult to give to Germany?
Germany is not yet used to it, it is still uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it is always difficult to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis – every time Germany takes on an important role, a variety of anti-German feelings are manifested.
The Germans can’t just handle it.
In fact, it’s an old problem: you don’t want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It has to take into account a wide variety of neighbors and opinions, which is not easy.
So, the influence of the US in European politics is constantly weakening, but at the moment the EU is not filling this vacuum, who then remains?
The Germans will just have to play a bigger role.
Even if you don’t like it, it’s unpleasant or it increases your dislike of you – that’s life!
Stephen Sabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute where academics and political scientists from Europe and North America jointly explore the problems of the transatlantic community.
In addition, Sabo is a member of the German Marshall Foundation, in which he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
