Now is the time to let the people decide at the ballot box, in which direction the country should go.
Mostly for the Islamist project, this is considered a settled matter.
The concept of “human rights” is never mentioned.
Hafiz Abu Saeed is furious at this forced constitutional process, which was supposed to last until February with the participation of all the public forces.
A 48-year-old human rights lawyer and chairman of the Egyptian Human Rights Organization (EHRO) defended the Muslim Brotherhood while they were in prison or on trial under Mubarak.
Not because he shared their worldview, but because human rights are indivisible to him.
For this he was beaten, convicted, arrested.
And now the words “human rights” never appear in the new constitution, he regrets in a conversation with “Welt am Sonntag”.
The expansion of Morsi’s influence on all three branches of government in the state disappoints the lawyer.
These measures represent a clear blow to the democratic rules of the game and will lead the Egyptians to a new dictatorship.
"Instead of strengthening the civil state, the president de facto cancelled it," Saeda said.
Without civil society organizations, democracy cannot function.
Saeed feels that everyone has left him, even the international community, which looks at the ideological struggle of the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
There may be retribution for this.
A demonstrator in Tahrir Square warns, “You are creating a monster you can’t control.”
Norwegian raccoon: the worst smelling fish in the world?
With a population of five million, Norway has one of the highest living standards not only in Europe, but also around the world.
Perhaps the secret of this country’s success is somehow connected with the local addiction to one extremely evil fish dish?
Take a few overripe pieces of cheese.
Put them in a pile of dirty and sweaty sports clothes.
Leave them there for a week.
You will have a smelly smell of raccoons - one of the most famous Norwegian delicacies.
I am in a small town called Fagernes, three hours drive from Oslo.
Surrounded by snow-covered picturesque views. It is very beautiful, but in the air will pour an indestructible characteristic smell.
A rakfish is a trout sprinkled with salt and wandering in the water for up to a year, depending on what kind of shower you need to achieve.
As the twilight thickens and cools, crowds of Norwegians gather for a festival in Fagernes, dedicated to this very, let’s say, exciting dish.
“It is eaten raw and washed with a sip of aquavit, local mint vodka,” explains Havard Halvarsen, a local firefighter by profession and co-ordinated by the “Racphysic General”, who leads the festival.
Everywhere around us, people eat fish cut into small cubes and wash it in large portions of alcohol.
“Someone likes aquavits more than raccoons,” says Howard.
This drink is able to break the smell.
I try a couple of pieces.
If you manage to carry a piece under your nose, then everything is not so bad - little different from the portion of land that you drove with you on the bus for a long time.
The rakfisk is a Norwegian product from a completely different time, a time of poverty, when, even before the advent of refrigerators, the fish was soaked in hermetically sealed barrels of salt water in the autumn.
Then in the deep winter, when the fish has already well and thoroughly fertilized, it was extracted and, suppressing the perception of alcohol, eaten.
In the memory of the last generation, the fact that thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work and emigrate mainly to the United States.
Now, the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, who are drawn here by jobs, high wages and a developed social security system.
Residents of Sweden (a long-time rival, and not so long ago and a much more profitable neighbor) come to work here massively.
The rift is perceived as an important symbol, an indispensable, albeit somewhat grim, element of Norway's past.
This is one of the most expensive local dishes.
On the other hand, everything is expensive here - a small glass of beer or sandwich will cost you 9 pounds ($14).
Norway rarely appears in the world news, and most of the country’s residents seem to be satisfied with it.
People here still reluctantly mention the name of Anders Breivik, a racist and right-wing extremist who shot and killed 77 men, women and children last year.
Without mentioning his name, the attack is called "the July 22nd".
It is very difficult for Norwegians to believe that in their peace-loving country one of their fellow citizens was capable of such atrocities and murders.
At the heart of today’s well-being of Norway lies the growth (since the 1970s) of one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world.
“Oil, however, is not the only reason for our prosperity,” says Anna, our waitress, who carries trays of ragged raccoons, a woman with long, light hair and strikingly blue eyes, the embodiment of Nordic well-being.
We are a people – as you call it – intelligent.
Like most Norwegians, she speaks English very well.
We don't like to show up, we don't brag.
Norway is very careful with its oil - most of the revenues of the oil and gas industry are invested in a special fund created for the benefit of future generations.
In the years leading up to the global financial crisis, when everyone was squandering money that they didn’t have, Norway carefully calculated all the costs.
“As long as you can ski in the winter and go hiking in the summer, that’s enough for happiness,” says Anna.
"And there's a raccoon," she adds with a carefree laugh.
I'm standing in the snow in line for some food - the raccoon is enough for me.
Here's a hamburger with salmon meat - it's definitely exotic, tasty juicy meat.
But in the evening we will have even more of the same fish with an unforgettable smell.
In my hotel there is a special dinner dedicated to raccoons, during which visitors vote to determine the best or perhaps the most fragrant fish.
There is a live TV show, in which they show the leader in a tie-butterfly, surrounded by plates with raccoons.
It's like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"So, Thor-Jürgen, what rating did you put for the best fish out there in the mountains?"
"Yes, Howard, here's our assessment."
Everyone laughs and applauds.
Someone falls from the chair, possibly by crossing the aquavit.
Or maybe just by inhaling the smell of this fish.
Mexican President Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto is facing a difficult start to his career.
As Mexican President-elect Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant invites us to look at the difficulties he will face and the mixed expectations of his country’s population.
Traffic in Mexico City is now in a particularly bad state.
This city is overcrowded with transport and at the best time, and since Monday, steel fences have been erected, cutting through several key highways to the capital and causing chaos on the roads.
However, this was done not to prevent people from getting to work from the suburbs, but to prevent protesters from getting to the parliament building.
On Sunday, the new head of Mexico, Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto, will wear a presidential tie and take over the country.
He has a difficult task ahead of him.
Mexico has achieved good economic performance under the administration of Felipe Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n, who is now in office, but the country has plunged into a war on drugs, which has already claimed some 60,000 lives in six years.
“My government declares to the people of Mexico its readiness to fight violence,” Mr. Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama earlier this week in the oval office of the White House.
I am going to propose a new security strategy that will allow us to achieve this goal.
Before such statements, next to the President of the United States, Mr. Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto’s political career developed as the governor of his native state of Mexico.
In his homeland, in a densely populated and expansive state surrounding the country’s capital, opinions about the new leader were divided.
Straight-line human
In the idyllic town of Valle de Bravo, for example, it is remembered with warmth.
Residents are credited with the revival of tourism, the development of the resort area and the creation of infrastructure.
The city can be reached by one of the new highways built by Mr. Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto, which are strikingly different from the roads with bumps and pits that were previously on this site.
The signs with his name hang on the modern building of the sports center and on the impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
“We are linking hopes with him for real and serious change,” says his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, a state congressman from the Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto-led Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI).
We look forward to the real and decisive changes that are so urgently needed in our country, primarily in the area of security and economic development.
After 81 years of uninterrupted power, the PRI was ousted in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera acknowledges that after his 12-year absence at the Los Pinos presidential palace, the party has placed high hopes on Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto.
He also denies the accusations of incontinence brought against the new president by the opposition.
He is very straightforward and very committed to the realization of his vision of the future of the country.
He is an excellent statesman and, above all, a person who knows how to listen.
But in the other part of the state, many people have a different idea about the former governor.
The municipality of Nessaualcoitl, also known as Ciudad Nessa, is the most striking contrast with the cobbled streets of Valle de Bravo.
Hidden under the escalators of the highways, it is in many ways a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the municipality are also of a harsh nature of this metropolis.
Troops were deployed earlier this year to pacify drug gangs in these areas, and violence against women is particularly acute.
Dozens of dead women have been found in a desert near a large landfill in the last two years alone.
More than a thousand women were killed in Mexico City during the governorate of Mr. Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto - a figure well above that in the infamous city of Ciudad Ju<0xC3><0xA1>rez, whose name has become defamatory when it comes to the killing of innocent women.
According to his opponents, Mr. Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto, at best, could be said to have failed to deal with the problem of the murder of women during his tenure as governor.
In the worst case, his administration is accused of ignoring the problem completely.
An inhabitant of a concrete house, similar to most houses in this slum area, Irenaeus Buendia hardly holds back tears, showing me pictures of her late daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes that she was killed by her cohabitant.
“When I got to her house, it looked like her body had been washed before that,” recalls Mrs. Buendia.
There were signs that she had been beaten, and the body was already swollen.
Mariana’s mother tells the story, and the portrait of her daughter looks at us from the wall, where it hangs next to the crucifix, on which is written only one word: justice.
This, they said, is what this family was denied.
“State officials treated me like an old gossip, a disgruntled disturber of peace.
They want people to just accept everything they say and shut up.
But this is wrong, it is not possible, especially when there are so many violations and shortcomings around," she says.
Putting on a presidential tie on Saturday, President Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto will take on a difficult responsibility with her.
Over the past six years, tens of thousands of families in Mexico have been affected by crimes related to violence, and the new president has promised to make solving this problem a priority during his reign.
“I hope he will be exactly the same president as he was the governor,” Olvera, a congressman from Valle de Bravo’s PRI party, said.
However, this is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Nesa fear the most.
Bradley Manning did not complain of ill-treatment, the indictment states.
Prosecutors are trying to refute Bradley Manning's claims about poor conditions in detention.
During the hearing, increased attention was paid to Manning's stay in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense demands that the case be closed on the grounds that Manning's terms of detention were cruel.
The U.S. Army is accused of stealing several thousand secret documents.
On Friday, the indictment tried to prove that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified material in U.S. history, did not take advantage of many opportunities to file a complaint of ill-treatment, which he said he had to transfer while in military prison.
During a cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Mide, Maryland, military prosecutor Major Ashden Fein said that records of Manning's weekly visits by prison administration officials for nine months of his detention in Quantico, Virginia, were not available.
A cross-examination of the defence's request to terminate Manning's case on the grounds that the terms of his detention were cruel and in themselves sufficient punishment was carried out the next day after Manning stated that he intended to commit suicide while in custody.
A military intelligence analyst who was arrested in June 2010 has been charged with stealing several thousand classified documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published on the Internet on the WikiLeaks website.
WikiLeaks did not confirm that Manning was the source of the information.
During the hearing on Friday, prosecutor Feyn, along with Manning, reviewed the reports that were filled in after Manning's visits by administration officials during his stay in Quantico Prison, where he was under strict detention conditions from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When prosecutor Feyn asked about the reports on Friday, Manning admitted that he assessed the prison administration’s treatment of him as “excellent” and the general conditions of detention as “very professionally organized.”
The reports in question do not contain complaints of ill-treatment, despite Manning being directly asked about the conditions of his detention, Feyn argues.
Manning replied that he had expressed oral concern about these problems and that his visiting administration representatives had discussed these problems with him and had stated that they would deal with them, but had not recorded them in writing.
“They were recording ‘no issues’ (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn’t mean I didn’t raise this topic in the conversation,” Manning says.
A military judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he hadn’t complained about the mistreatment of him in January 2011 during a commission meeting that looked at the suicidal intentions he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that during that meeting he wanted to have the “trauma prevention” regime removed and the conditions of detention eased.
Representatives of the military leadership explained that a limited detention regime - at a lower level than the surveillance regime to prevent suicide - was introduced to protect the prisoner, as well as for the safety of others.
“I wanted to let the administration know that I’m okay with them canceling the trauma prevention regime... so that my standard of living would improve, from my point of view,” Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to a prison at a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that his thoughts of suicide appeared in Kuwait, and that one day he lost consciousness due to the severe heat.
He explained that it is psychologically very difficult when you are not told how your destiny is decided and what is happening in the outside world.
"My world has shrunk to the size of my prison at Camp Africa," Manning said on Thursday.
“I thought I was going to die in this cage.”
While in Quantico, Manning said he spent most of his time in a small cell — at least 21 hours, and often even more than 23 hours a day — alone.
Manning reports that he was allowed to leave only a mattress, blanket, hats, several items of clothing and glasses.
He says he tried to move, as sleeping or even just lying down during the day was forbidden by the rules.
According to Manning, during sleep in his eyes, he was constantly struck by a light penetrating outside the camera.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned in bed at night, then, according to him, he was awakened and forced to turn on his back.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal objection to Manning's ill-treatment in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Livenworth, Kansas.
In addition, on Friday, the judge asked Manning about the statement he made while testifying on Thursday that after one night he was forced to sleep naked in his Quantico cell, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other inmates on the morning check.
Manning said he was unable to cover himself with a blanket during the inspection.
Answering the judge's questions on Friday, Manning said he understood from the guard's order that he should throw a blanket to cover himself, but admitted that no one directly ordered him to throw it.
Manning said on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of his attempt to show the officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning said he told the officer that he could use rubber panties or flip flops to injure himself, but did not.
That night, according to Manning's testimony, his underwear, hats and glasses were taken from the camera.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account what he has had to endure during his detention, and significantly shorten his prison term if Manning is found guilty by a military court that is due to begin examining his case early next year.
The defense said it planned to offer Manning to plead guilty to less serious crimes and challenge other charges as excessive.
The resumption of hearings is scheduled for this weekend, and it is expected that the prosecution will insist that the conditions of detention have been justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was detained in Quantico in accordance with rules governing the detention of detainees under the strictest regime.
The charges against Manning include accomplices to the enemy, illegal promotion of data on the Internet, the transfer of information relating to national defense, and the theft of state property or documents.
If he is convicted on all counts of the indictment, he may face life imprisonment.
My crisis of national self-determination is the story of an American of Mexican descent.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico because of the lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who left because they remind the people of the country of difficult times.
Ruben Navarrete believes that Mexicans of American origin are rift between the two cultures.
During a recent trip to Mexico City, I walked down the arrivals corridor, approached the border control area and froze on the spot.
The signs indicated two lines: one for Mexicanos, the other for Extranjeros.
I stood in front of them for a few seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in Central California, and I've been called a Mexican my whole life.
It’s just a conditional name, like how my friends in Boston call themselves Irish, and my friends in New York consider themselves Italian.
Later, I stopped at the complex construction of "American of Mexican descent".
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather’s homeland, there was no need for conditional names or complex designs.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask questions or answer them.
But my vocabulary is poorer than that of native speakers, and I can’t get rid of the American accent.
That’s why I got my American passport and became in line for Extranjeros.
I remembered this story a few days ago when Mexican President-elect Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto visited the White House and met with President Obama.
On the agenda were issues familiar to the presidents of these countries: immigration, drugs and trade.
President Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto was eager to talk about the rise of the Mexican economy, thanks to which Mexicans will now, with the same success, be able to stay in Mexico instead of moving to the United States.
He wants to sign a partnership agreement with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc like the European Union.
In addition, President Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto promised to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no concrete proposals were made.
For Mexico, relations with the United States are a heavy and old-fashioned matter.
Most Americans never thought that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and under the guise of a rifle forced its leaders to give up half of their territory.
But Mexicans think for centuries, not minutes, and see reminders of those events in everything.
Therefore, it is only worth it for any U.S. statesman to silence even a word of criticism towards Mexico, in the press and among the elite of Mexican society, complaints are immediately distributed that Americans violate the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the descendants of Montezuma are filled with militancy.
Mexico’s relationship with more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States is the most difficult.
Do you want to talk about insults?
They're enough.
There are winners and losers in Mexico, people who find opportunities for themselves in this country, and those for whom there are no such opportunities.
In Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio, there are so many people of Mexican descent for only one reason: at some point in their family history, someone—a father or a grandfather—had no opportunity to realize themselves in Mexico and was forced to go north.
Most often it was Mexicans of a certain type - dim, uneducated, from poor peasant families.
We are their descendants, and we remember it.
In Mexico, they see it differently.
Today our life is the embodiment of the American dream, we have studied in good schools and settled for good jobs, but let us not forget that even this dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confusing and unclear, but we know which country to consider as our own.
United States of America.
In addition, we know that most of the Mexican elite and the ruling class do not like us.
We answer them the same.
They see us as a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us as second class people, as unreal Mexicans.
We do not speak Spanish well enough, and our ties with Mexico are not strong enough.
Our very existence for them is explained by failures.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they would not have left.
We would not be behind the silk curtain now, finding a full life in the United States, but losing spiritual ties.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and legally moved to the United States as a child, and this reminds me that there are certain frictions between real Mexicans and Americans of Mexican descent - Mexicans clearly understand their national identity, and Americans of Mexican descent.
She is a U.S. citizen and believes that she belongs to both of these countries.
At the same time, many of my acquaintances, Americans of Mexican descent, do not feel that they belong to any of them.
We listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also love Bruce Springsteen.
When you get the best of both worlds, you inevitably lose your roots.
In Mexico, we are Americans.
In the United States, we are called Mexicans.
Now, as I have found out during my trip, as if our relationship is already not sufficiently confused, some Mexican leaders and representatives of the intelligentsia want to restore relations with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as ambassadors of Mexico and represent its interests in the United States.
We could tell our American friends about what a beautiful country it is and how great to visit it, and we could convince political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah, sure.
Nothing's gonna work out.
Too many insults in the past.
And given the gap between the rich and the poor, the rampant corruption and drug trafficking, many of us don’t think this country is so beautiful at all.
I'm sorry, but deal with this yourself, amigos.
And that's fair.
If some Mexicans still cannot forgive the United States for what they did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they will have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans are still offended by the way they have treated their relatives in Mexico recently.
Oh, yeah.
Maybe we have more in common than I thought.
The Old Battles in the New Middle East
The ceasefire agreement between Israel and the Hamas group could be a fragile foundation for further peace
Is a long-term peace between the Arabs and the Israelis in the Middle East possible?
The next round of bloodshed leads to the conclusion of the futility of such hopes.
It sounds like the usual, meaningless arguments about who started first; many buildings have been turned into ruins; more than 140 Palestinians, most of whom were civilians, and six Israelis have been killed; for the first time during the conflict, the city's missiles fired from the Gaza Strip's territory were dropped into the vicinity.
However, despite the Israelis and Palestinians hopelessly entangled in their perennial conflict, changes have come to the Middle East.
This can be treated differently, but the events of the “Arab Spring” have surrounded many established realities in a rebellious storm, and the Palestinians and the Israelis have not managed to stay away from the swirl that has shaken the region.
Perhaps, as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons to hope for a way out of this deadly impasse.
War without victors
At first glance, the situation does not give reasons for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, which was signed on November 21, will be implemented, the clashes that took place this week only strengthened the positions of the security forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Islamist Hamas movement, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, say they have forced Israel to retreat despite the losses it suffered.
Despite the fact that some of the group’s leaders have been wiped out and 1.7 million people have been stranded in one of the most densely populated and troubled places on the planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is growing in popularity on the West Bank of the Jordan River, another Palestinian territory currently controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well come to the conclusion that time is working for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, Hamas has new powerful and rich friends.
The resurgent regional leader Turkey, once Israel’s closest ally among Muslim countries, supported Hamas, followed by Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamically developing countries in the Persian Gulf.
Celebrating Hamas supporters declare the creation of an Islamist crescent around Israel - from Lebanon in the north, which is ruled by a paramilitary group of Hezbollah, to Syria, in which increasingly pro-Islamist rebels are about to overthrow the power of the Hashemite coalition where the Ughis of Bashar al-Assad, and Dahles.
The most significant change in the balance of power in the region occurred on the southern borders of Israel, in the most populous and important Arab country, in Egypt, where, under President Mohammed Morsi, the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood was strengthened.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator who paid little attention to supporting Hamas.
The Muslim Brotherhood, on the contrary, is an organization much like Hamas, and its leaders are more prone to populism.
In future diplomatic deployments, Hamas could become a significant player whose voice will not be able to silence even Israel and America.
At the same time, supporters of the “hard” line in Israel will come to opposite conclusions.
In a military sense, Hamas was defeated.
Israel’s Iron Dome anti-missile system has justified the cost of its creation and successfully destroyed many of the launched Hamas missiles.
Citizens of Israel can sleep peacefully for at least some time.
As far as diplomacy is concerned, the US has remained true to its unchanging position; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for the start of the last round of violence.
Another important factor is Israel’s economic prosperity, especially under Benjamin Netanyahu’s government, which largely ignored the peace process.
Despite the fact that since 2004, about 30 Israelis have died from missiles fired from the territory of the Gaza Strip, Israel has managed to minimize the problem of terrorist-killers, partly due to the wall that enters the territory of the West Bank of the Jordan - a significant part is not accepted.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party - in preparation for the January 22 elections - has teamed up with even more aggressive conservatives led by Avigdor Lieberman, is very convenient.
What is the point of impersonating the Palestinians and giving them their own state?
If all the power in the West Bank is given to them, will they not start launching rockets into Israel from there, as their counterparts in the Gaza Strip do?
It is better to keep them behind the wall and severely suppress any attempts to raise their heads.
It is possible that the supporters of the "hard" line will win; however, their calculations can be refuted by the Arab Spring.
While the Islamists who come to power in Egypt and other countries do not have the warmest feelings for Israel, their priority will be internal problems.
The defense portion of Israel’s budget is larger than all of its Arab neighbors combined.
Unleashing a war with a regional superpower is unlikely to help Arab governments strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of Egypt’s president, Morsi, who worked with Barack Obama on a ceasefire, is a good sign and could mark the beginning of change.
Israel must take into account the long-term consequences of its policies.
As democratic change in Arab countries comes along, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination is a slow-motion bomb that will sooner or later explode in Israeli-occupied territories, like a bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression is already undermining the foundations of democratic order in the Jewish state, and the demographic aspect - the growth of the Arab population - is only exacerbating these problems.
The bloody operations that are carried out every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement have to pay for the growing discontent of the international community.
Both sides need an external impulse.
There remains the only solution that is constantly being called upon by sensible representatives on both sides, as well as much of the rest of the world and our newspaper: the formation of two states and Israel’s concession of territories in exchange for security.
There remains hope, not too impressive in the short term, that the ceasefire will allow other countries to influence the parties to the conflict more effectively.
Egypt, which has long taken the decision to cut off arms supplies to the Gaza Strip, as well as Turkey and Qatar, have a more favourable position than ever before in order to persuade Hamas to recognize the borders of the Jewish state adopted since 1967 in view of the exchange of territories and the sharing of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also make efforts to reconcile the Hamas and Fatah movements.
This would do more for the creation of a Palestinian state than the upcoming vote at the UN, which could result in recognition of the virtual statehood of Palestine.
President Obama must also play a role in putting Israel at the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never presented his own plan for a peaceful settlement.
Upon his return to the White House, he continues to show a reluctance to engage in the solution of the problem.
This is a catastrophically short-sighted position.
The United States is vitally interested in stability in the Middle East.
This is only possible in the case of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
In Australia, the law on unified packaging for cigarettes has entered into force.
Warnings about the harm of smoking and the image of disease-affected parts of the body are contrasted on dull green boxes, the same for all brands of cigarettes.
The first in world practice, the Australian law on the same type of packaging of cigarettes and tobacco products came into force, replacing the logos and color design of different brands with the same box of dull olive color with scary pictures of their parents who are affected by the disease of the parts of the body and images of children.
In addition to various pictures and inscriptions warning about the harm of smoking, the only difference between the packages introduced in mandatory order from this Saturday - the names of the brands, which are printed in the same fine print.
These are the most severe conditions in the world for packaging tobacco products.
The Federal Government of Australia states that the aim of this measure is to keep young people from smoking, depriving them of this harmful habit of fashion status.
This decision was based on the results of studies that showed that people who did not start smoking before the age of 26, in 99 cases out of 100 never become smokers.
“Obviously, even at a very young age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to convey through packaging design,” Health Minister Tanya Plibersek explains, citing research that has shown that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated with children.
Australia is one of the countries with the lowest proportion of smokers in the world, so these changes will not have a significant impact on the profits of transnational corporations, but other countries are already considering taking such measures.
Representatives of the tobacco industry strongly opposed the adoption of this law.
Tobacco companies claim that this will only increase the share of the black market, where cheap and affordable cigarettes will be sold.
“This law will lead to serious consequences other than those conceived by its initiators,” said Scott McIntyre, a spokesman for British American Tobacco in Australia.
Manufacturers of fake products from China and Indonesia will supply much more such goods for sale on the streets of Australia.
For some, on the contrary, the new laws contribute to the growth of business.
Sandra Ha of the small family company Zico Import Pty Ltd claims that the demand for cigar holders and silicone cases hiding unpleasant pictures on the packaging has increased rapidly (almost from zero) since two months ago, such companies as the British American Tobacco, the British Imperial Tobacco and the Tobacco
