Missing in the world of electronic networks and constant connections is not so bad.
On Thanksgiving, I had to spend five hours at the airport because our plane had mechanical problems and was replaced by another plane that we had been waiting for.
So I had plenty of time to reflect on the nature of boredom.
I'm not going to fool you.
Half a day at the airport while waiting for a flight is really boring, and there will not be much help neither books, magazines, iPhone, nor even duty-free shops.
However, more and more scientists and specialists in children's development have recently expressed themselves in favour of boredom.
They say that in certain situations it is not so bad for us and our children to miss.
This forces the brain to be distracted by interesting related topics, which may contribute to creativity.
And since in the modern world we are all constantly in front of some screen, the benefits of boredom pass by us.
Do we need to be bored?
Oh, yeah.
At the same time, no.
We'll get back to that.
In the past, I, like many, believed that boredom was an invention relative to recent times when people had more free time.
This is not the case, claims Peter Tuy, professor of Greek and Roman history at the Canadian University of Calgary, author of the book “A fascinating history of boredom” (Boredom: A Lively History, Yale University Press, 2011).
“In fact, boredom can boast a very ancient history,” he says.
On the walls in Pompeii are found Latin inscriptions about boredom, dating back to the first century.
The question remains as to how we understand boredom.
The problem is, says John D. Eastwood, assistant professor at York University in Ontario, Canada, that the understanding and vision of boredom has often changed.
After studying the research materials on the subject and asking a question to a target group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the following definition: boredom is when people “want but can’t do what would bring them satisfaction.”
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that a bored person doesn’t do something he’d like to do.
I don’t want to do anything with apathy.
The main thing in experiencing boredom, he says, is "a disturbance of attention and the associated deterioration of mood and the feeling that time is stretching slowly."
The description of boredom may seem very similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood argues that despite the possible link between these conditions, bored people see the causes of problems in the world and circumstances, and people experiencing depression see the problems in themselves.
Sometimes we feel like we’re bored when we’re really just having a hard time focusing on something.
In his study, “Unemployed Mind: Defining Boredom from a Point of View,” published in the September issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues refer to a previous experiment, whose participants listened to a recording of a voice reading the journal.
Some participants also heard the loud sounds of an off-the-shelf television program included in a neighboring room, others heard the same sounds at a low volume, so they could hardly be disassembled, and the third group listened only to the voice recording without a foreign soundtrack.
Those who listened to low-volume television noted that they were bored, more often than others — they found it difficult to concentrate, but they did not know the reasons for this and attributed it to boredom.
When we try to focus attention on a difficult or exciting task, interruption can cause boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, an adjunct professor of neurology at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the authors of this study.
On the other hand, when we do something uninteresting, "for example, looking at the flow of products on the conveyor in search of marriage, distracting music can help avoid boredom."
It is believed that when people start swinging on a chair or drawing caracula on a sheet of paper, they do it out of boredom, but now we know that in fact such actions just help not to relax physically.
“The study found that children who are not forbidden to snore and turn around learn better and remember more information than children who are required to sit quietly,” says Professor Fenske.
At some point we all feel bored: with a flight delay (as in my case), listening to a monotonous speech, watching an uninteresting film.
However, different people show a different degree of propensity for boredom.
In the 1980s, researchers developed a special “boring propensity scale” to measure such individual characteristics.
Questions and statements such as "A lot of what I have to do is monotonous" or "I'm interested in too much, so I don't have time for anything" are used to determine the rating on this scale.
With the help of such questionnaires, the researchers determined that boys miss girls more often, says Steven Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially when there are a variety of external stimuli.
In general, however, teenagers often miss out.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of personal and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teens and their parents 7-8 times a day with the help of a pager.
He received the following results: 32% of teens said they were bored at school and while doing homework, and 23% said they were bored outside of school.
Only 3% of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson notes that he has no data on what such data would be about boredom now, 21 years later.
However, he knows that “adolescence has a peak of a tendency to boredom”, mainly because children and adolescents are not allowed to fully decide what to do.
Let’s go back to my original question: Is boredom helpful?
Sometimes not, because in extreme manifestations, as research shows, it can push people to absurd and dangerous physical actions, risky gambling, or abuse of certain substances in an attempt to get rid of boredom.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have thought about the connection between boredom and creativity, says Professor Vodanovic, who has devoted more than two decades to the study of this problem.
“So our brain tells us that we should do something else; that’s boredom,” says Gary Marcus, a psychology professor at New York University.
But the brain doesn’t always know what to do.
If you get bored and you direct that energy to playing the guitar or cooking experiences, you’ll do yourself better.
However, if you start watching TV, you will only get better for a while, and soon it will pass.
Therefore, if your child misses you and you give him an iPad, he will no longer miss you, but he will not learn to fight boredom on his own or in any other way manage his time and work, says Professor Fenske.
"And such skills of self-regulation are used in a variety of situations," he says.
Your child not only learns to do something on his own, he also learns self-control in general.
I don't think that boredom should be exalted somehow.
However, it is also not worth considering it as a bad thing.
It is better to learn to feel comfortable even outside the continuous flow of actions and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees with that.
“We see this as having to be bored more often, while boredom is an extremely unpleasant, insatiable desire to do something meaningful,” he says.
In fact, people tend to somehow disconnect from constant worries and just relax.
“In the modern world, we are accustomed to constant overstimulation of the senses,” he says, “and when silence comes, we get lost and don’t know what to do.”
