The World's Toughest Occupation: Miners from Kavah-Igen
For four euros, Indonesian miners risk their lives and health by dragging 70 kilograms of sulfur on the top of the volcano along steep rocky paths
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
Among them, Anto Vijaya, one of 400 miners who make a living from mining sulfur in the Kawah-Igen volcano, located in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Every day, Anto descends to the very bottom of the crater, where sulfurous gas rising from the depths of the Earth freezes in contact with air.
He cuts out huge pieces of sulfur, the total weight of which can reach 70 kg, he puts them in two bamboo baskets, pulls the baskets on his shoulders and carries them up the steep stone road.
To the summit of the volcano, whose height is 2,386 meters, only 250 meters, but the exhausted loaders take more than 40 minutes to climb the tortoise step, with difficulty maintaining balance and carefully paving the road so as not to slip and fall off the cliff.
They know that one wrong step can cost them their lives, as happened with a tourist from France who crashed a few years ago from the cliffs of Kavah-Igen.
Miners from Kavah-Igen earn 5 eurocents for every kilogram of sulphur they extract
Upon reaching the top, they pave the way between tourists who photograph them as if they were monkeys from the circus and, tired of carrying heavy baskets, they walk three kilometers to the weights that the mining company has placed a little higher, at an altitude of 1,850 meters.
