The passionate basketball traveler Hector "Hetin" Reyes has been associated with this sport for more than 60 years and, thanks to him, has traveled the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico remember as many basketball stories as Hector “Hetin” Reyes.
After all, before a brain hemorrhage tied him to a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in sports for more than 60 years, as a small-scale player, a senior basketball league player, an authorized and head of the BSN with Cowboys Bayamone.
“I’ve played a lot of basketball roles throughout my life, including several at the same time as when I was president of BSN, general manager of the National Team, and president of the federation in the 1990s,” Reyes recalls during Primera Hora’s visit to his home in Bayamon, where he lives more than 50 years with Isabel, his fiancée.
“Basketball was my life.
Reyes does not exaggerate by making this claim.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photographs and memorial items collected for his long journey, testify to this.
Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n in the heart
With the greatest emotion, he keeps those who remember his way through the Cowboys, from the mid-50s as a player until 1982, when he turned 15 years old as a co-agent or contract agent.
"These were my best years, which I enjoyed the most, because I had the opportunity to be part of eight Cowboy Championships since 1967, as an agent, co-agent or manager.
There were many years of joy, including five championships held from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye to one in 1981, the year of Jerome Minsey's BSN debut.
From that moment onwards, Kuko Ortis, who was a great administrator, was in charge," Reyes said.
