Actor Larry Hagman has died.
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931 in Fort Worth, Texas, became world-famous for his leading role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R.", in the television series Dallas, in which he portrayed a businessman without principles, evil and mania.
Larry Hagman, whose role as oil tycoon Jay Ar Ewing in the television series Dallas became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in the new season of Dallas, died Friday night from complications caused by cancer, according to a family statement provided to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., a Dallas-based production studio.
"Larry has returned to his beloved hometown of Dallas, again playing the iconic role he liked the most," his family said.
Larry’s family and closest friends were with him in Dallas at the Thanksgiving Fair.
Linda Gray, who played his wife in the original series and in the sequel, was next to Hagman when he died at Dallas Hospital, her representative Jeffrey Lane said.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, cheerful, affectionate and talented, and I will miss him very much.
“He was an original personality and lived a full life,” Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis in 1992 and admitted to drinking for many years.
In 1995, he was found to have a malignant tumor in his liver and underwent a transplant.
Long before Dallas, Hagman gained notoriety on television due to his role as a decent type in the light comedy I Dream of Jeannie, which aired on NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life changes when he meets an attractive genie girl, played by Barbara Eden, and begins to live with her under one roof.
He was also the main character of two comedies that rarely appeared on the air, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His film work included critically acclaimed roles in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was his masterful interpretation of the delightfully disgusting J.R. that brought Hagman to the top of fame.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other characters surrounded by it aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The advertising slogan "Who shot J.R.?", designed to create a buzz around an episode full of emotions in which Hagman's character is almost killed, spawned international discussions and millions of dollars that were risked at bookmakers' offices.
It also helped to attract a record audience to the series at that time.
When the answer was given in an episode from November 1980, an average of 41 million viewers watched it and made Dallas the second most viewed entertainment program in history, after the 1983 finale of MASH, which attracted 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law, Christine (played by Mary Crosby), who shot him.
J.R. interrupted her and then threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave town, but others had reasons to attack him.
Hagman played Ewing as an insatiable corrupter with a charismatic smile: a dishonest businessman and unfaithful husband who wanted his alcoholic wife, Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), placed on treatment.
“I know what should be on J.R.’s gravestone,” Hagman said in 1988.
It must be said, "Here lies the honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
It's the only deal he lost.
Victoria Princepal, also the heroine of the original series, recalled Hagman on Friday as someone "huge, both on and off the screen."
It is unforgettable and irreplaceable for millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of every one of us who have been lucky enough to know and love it.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were shown a few months ago with great success on the TNT channel.
The recording of five episodes of the second season has already been completed and the sixth was in production, the channel said.
Warner or TNT have not yet made a statement about what will happen to the series after Hagman's departure.
A native of Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who shone in such classic works as "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan".
Martin was still a teenager when she gave birth to him in 1931 during her marriage to lawyer Ben Hagman.
He tried his luck on the theatrical stages of New York in the early 1950s, and then served in the English Air Force from 1952 to 1956.
While there, he met the young Swedish artist Mai Axelsson and married her.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and they lived for a long time in the Californian city of Malibu, where many celebrities live.
In 2001, he called his memoirs "Hello Darlin': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life".
“I didn’t include anything that I thought was capable of hurting anyone or affecting them in any way,” he told Prensa Asociada at the time.
After a liver transplant, he began to promote organ donation and worked as a volunteer in the hospital to help patients experiencing fear.
“I give them advice, I give them courage, I meet them when they go to surgery and after,” he said.
I'm trying to offer some consolation, like "don't be afraid, it'll be a little uncomfortable for a short time, but you'll be fine."
He also actively opposed smoking and participated in several campaigns.
Starts a course that explores "The End of the World"
Every week, students explore apocalyptic phenomena such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charme decided to read a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible bait: the end of the “long countdown” of the Mayan calendar, December 21, which many people took as proof that the end of the world was coming.
But Charme had no idea what was waiting for him in the next couple of months: the catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, the financial crisis that some call "longarmageddon," and the growing conflict that drags Israel, a place where Christian end-time theorists believe Apocalypse will begin.
“I didn’t realize it was going to be the most apocalyptic semester of all,” Charme told students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey this week.
If we analyze what is happening in the world today, as if we had only 30 days left, it was a really good period.
And remember, bad is good for those who have an apocalyptic mindset.
And he’s not the only professor to offer “end of the world” courses this semester, theoretically the last in history.
At the University of Tempe, Associate Professor Barry Walker reads the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
“We’re analyzing why these ideas spread over time,” he said, and the way they suggest hypothetical scenarios that cause certain human actions.
If nuclear material gets into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students analyzed films on apocalyptic themes and studied how they relate to real-life examples.
"I tried to tell the students what is probably plausible and impossible," Walker said.
On the main campus of the State University of Pennsylvania, Professor of Latin American History Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, associate professor of art history and anthropology, teamed up to read a course called simply “The End of the World.”
"We're not adding '2012' to always be able to read the course again in case the end of the world doesn't come," Restall said.
Despite the "imminent destruction", students must learn, prepare projects and pass final exams.
In Penn State, the final exam will be taken on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students no choice but to work “until the same night the world is supposed to end,” Restall said.
The courses were quite popular.
“Places ended in two hours,” Restall said of his course for high-average students, which was attended by 35 students.
We received emails for many weeks before the start of the semester from people who asked if there was still room.
Students, in turn, assure that this course is one of the most interesting.
“I like to watch what people do to comfort themselves,” said Bridged Robinson, a 23-year-old student at the Department of Religion and Sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, to Rutgers-Camden.
And the apocalyptic form of thought, secular or religious, is only a matter of consolation or its absence.
Will Vecks, a 25-year-old student in the Department of Psychology and Nursing, said he watched all the apocalyptic movies.
“I’ve never heard of a course that would teach that,” he said.
I like him.
But none of the students interviewed—not to mention the professor—did say they believed in the end of the world date on December 21.
“Our first project touched on the Mayan prophecy, and in some ways we discredited it,” said Julie Seeglen, a 21-year-old senior fellow at Temple University in West Chester.
The Maya never predicted the end of the world; it’s just a key moment in the calendar, Restall said.
But he noted that there is an apocalyptic concern in Western culture, which is numbered several centuries, where people react to changes around them, predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused an increase in these speculations.
“In other places people don’t think about it,” he said.
Mostly in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dogerty, a professor of religion at La Salle University, who is teaching courses in the Philippines this year, quickly answered the question of whether he knows of any course on the “end of the world” there.
"The Philippines does not take part at the end of the world," he wrote, hinting at a higher court order.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
Restall noted that for a long time there had been talk of many days of the Last Judgment, and said that if nothing happened on December 21, “people would immediately start thinking about the next date” or philosophizing that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period after which the world would end.
Students and teachers are careless about this date.
Some said they were going to go to "end of the world" parties.
“Maybe I’ll call some of my friends to laugh together,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old student at the communications department.
